textDisplay:
The trouble with this documentary is that they present themselves and their work as untouched by power and money. There is a bit of a bait and switch going here. They begin with the cigarette industry which no one in their right mind could disagree with and then move on to the environment and claim the the scientific community is united, which it isn't. What's more, the doom predicted for decades for this planet has ranged from a coming ice age to the rising oceans swallowing islands and coastlines. The predictions continue to be adjusted as time has gone on. And who benefits from these predictions? The powerful do, because it has become a point of division used to sway elections - to secure more power. And so the very sad truth is that no matter whether the science is accurate or not the powerful will use it for their own ends. If the earth is dying they will use it to their own power and glory. If the earth is just fine they will use it to their power and glory. If we continue to burn fossil fuels they will make money. If we switch to green energy they will make money. They will pivot and pivot and pivot to redirect any attack. Science is now their tool. Both the lab sciences and the psychological sciences. They will and ARE using both to achieve their goals. And their goals do not include you. They don't care what happens to you.

The last thing they want you to do is use common sense. They need you to indulge. Indulge in fossil fuels. Indulge in green energy. Drink only Coca Cola or drink only bottled water. It doesn't matter to them, because they own it all and their power will increase. All you have to do is keep on indulging.

textDisplay: This was fantastic. I think a piece of the misinformation factory that wasn’t examined is how anti-intellectualism is transmitted across generations. Claims of STEM being “too hard” work in lockstep with the Law of the Market and demands for profitability. What even counts as prestigious “hard” science is set by the market, to devalue the fields that provide critique: sociology, history, psychology, philosophy of science, and multidisciplinary approaches… indeed, this documentary highlighted folks from those fields to great effect. But I worry that the final blow, now that science is viewed as unreasonably difficult for the average kid, is that the average adult is socially exempted from even trying to follow evidence-based arguments. What a perfect breeding ground for misinformation.
textOriginal: This was fantastic. I think a piece of the misinformation factory that wasn’t examined is how anti-intellectualism is transmitted across generations. The only problem is blind trust. Most people blindly trust so much, and blind trust is dangerous no matter who we are. Doing so can take you on a roller coaster ride in no time.
Sadly most people want to live in ignorance, yet claim boldly the opposite, because of the fear of what other people may think of them. Most people are heavy on the double standard, and it's all just very sad.
So, the reason why there's confusion moving about is simply because most people aren't used to question things as much as one should do, which is why these mindsets see it all as something wrong. A mindset that are terrified of truth, will do just about anything to avoid it, and then comes the blame. We are all responsible for finding our own answers in life, yet most people are being programmed from early age to sit and wait to be fed, in which most people continue doing so far into adulthood. As an adult all you got to do is look for the answers yourself, in which you gain control because now you won't have to wait for anyone but yourself. Just think about all the time you've waited in your life, for things you can simply start doing yourself. There's no need of permission from anyone but yourself to explore your own mind and get creative, yet most adults still think they need permission from someone else sadly.
Just a simple food for thought: If someone else can find an answer, then so can you. The amount of time it takes is irrelevant, because that boils down to personal experience. We can only start at where our very own feet are placed, and that's why it's crucial to be honest with oneself.

Just understand that anyone can be right at any given point in time, as well as anyone can be wrong at any given point in time. What someone has studied, what job they got, how old they are etc etc is irrelevant. Anything needs to be questioned all the way till you hold the truth, and that is why I'm sick and tired of so many who tell me: I heard this scientist named blah blah state this, that and the other... Well, information like that is worthless to me, because 99.99% of people who dump that info in my lap, want me to find their answers for them. If such people would express to me how they feel about it, and they can prove to me that what they are stating of this other person is actually true, then there's at least something to consider if it of course sounds reasonable.

We are all human beings and anyone can be wrong as anyone can be right. That is the truth. That's why nobody should ever blindly trust science as anything else, because it is actually dangerous. The people who try to force anyone with blind trust are the one's one should trust the least, because it clearly indicates such people have other agendas.

This is the kind of person you should never ever blindly trust, because she think she cannot be wrong which is a lie. She's a human being like everybody else and she can even outright lie whenever she feels like it just like everybody else.

If you want confidence within other people you need to show yourself as better than what who you claim to be opposed to are showing, it's that simple. It's irrelevant what anybody else has done or not if you show the same or even worse. This is why blind trust is dangerous because people just like her will try to make people blindly trust her as if she will always be right till the day she dies. That is a lie by default.

textDisplay:
@ 5:47: This is silly. The idea that the preponderance of studies should be biased toward one possible explanation is antithetical to the scientific method, especially if that explanation is the favored one. Good science seeks to disconfirm hypotheses, rather than to confirm them, because one can always find reasons to believe something if one really wants to. Often, it is the inability to falsify a theory that is truly telling. In fact, this entire presentation appears to be attempting to dismiss the 'wisdom of crowds' in favor of the pronunciations of elites, as seen by the radical dismissal of alternative viewpoints on social media. SMH.
Also - I find it extremely interesting that @ 42:26, the 8th image on row 4, when discussing "fake news" and "conspiracy theories" actually features Dr. Todd Grande, who is actively working to OPPOSE conspiracy theories regarding COVID-19. I wonder how many of the other images were included simply to inflate the apparent number of purveyors of "fake news."
Furthermore, I would argue that political concerns, as much as financial ones, are currently in a position to influence science, and thereby distort the outcome of what should be independent inquiries into the truth. Governments (and therefore politicians) control enormous amounts of funding for scientific research.

textDisplay:
I find it rather dubious that you paint all sceptics here with one sweep of the brush and brand them as people who intentionally present misinformation as fact. You completely miss the point sincere sceptics make in the climate debate. Besides, 'climate sceptics' has become a term that is equalled with ignorance or willful obstruction of science. While that may be the case of people serving industrial masters (and yes, they are plenty of those too), Nobel laureates like Ivar Gjaever ask significant questions to which climate science simply does not answer.

And it is by now a well (scientific) established fact that the IPCC for example isn't free of psychological/sociological tendencies like tunnel vision/affirmation bias/cognitive dissonance. Recently the IPCC admitted that CO2 probably wasn't the sole or even main reason the climate changes, albeit in very fine print and not communicated very loudly, because - as internal memos showed - IPCC directors felt it might disuade the public.

Last point. We also tend to forget that 'the environmental movement' in part has become an industry in its own right too, attracting billions in subsidies, sponsorships and..... industrial patronage by companies who have a stake in renewable energies.

If you tell the story of misinformation or the intentional sabotage of 'science' (as if that's a given standard for good practices all the time) then please tell the whole story and show all the facts, not just the ones that neatly fit in your narrative.

Then - and only then - will you see how utterly dificult something like the climate debate is or how science operates in an environment where facts are for sale for anyone with an agenda.

If you want to change that, there's only one probable course of action: decouple science from private funding completely and fund it properly with public funds, with oversight only (!) being posed on accountability for spending and guarding against corruption. As a safeguard against social and psychological dynamics: that's inevitable. In the end even science sometimes becomes political in that it presents clashes of dominant paradigms. But as long as the ones coming out on top are the ones who generate results (measurable, reproducable and verifiable) facts, it will be the best thing we have in confronting issues like climate change.

Those are my two cents...

textDisplay: Amazing work. I just want to comment on the rather narrowed conseptualisation of science and evidence-based research that the documentary advances. Although the kind of data we produce in this field can take other forms and shapes than those that come from laboratories, they're still science. Qualitative research and applied social science can help in both defining the problems discussed in the documentary and also advancing ways of moving out of this impasse.

textDisplay:
I think a fundamental distrust for science is healthy. Science, especially anything statistical or sociological is often faulty. I remember a university did an experiment not too long ago where they tried to replicate the results of other proven experiments that had already undergone the peer review process and been published in journals, and for a large number of those they arrived at significantly different results than the original experiments.
That is of course no reason to throw out the scientific method, because it is by far our best way of determining universal truths, but it is by no means a perfect method and everything "scientific" should be viewed with due skepticism.

textDisplay:
The deeper problem is that the general public has become so devoid of critical thinking abilities that corruption, intimidation and hidden agendas aren't seen through by the general public like they could be -- if only schools could and would cultivate the brain power and education they could in young people we'd be in much better shape to deal with the important problems of today. We have a public that is now SO STUPID that a lot of people can't figure out if there is a difference between males and females, or if there is such as thing as "boys" as compared to "girls". Science is what these modern idiots need to know, but so many of them can't find the Pacific Ocean on a map so it's a little inappropriate expecting them to think their ways out of paper bags about anything, let alone about whatever headlines about science they're being spoon fed.

You don't have to be any kind of genius to learn how to see through manipulated, corrupted, incompetent statistics such as the idiotic misunderstanding of wage statistics male versus female. These reasons behind those warped and grossly, grossly, grossly misleading statistics -- so grossly misleading that they're essentially false in terms of what they're claimed to prove -- are very clearly identified and understood and have been so for years. See Warren Farrell, for example, a former Director of the National Organization of Women. He wrote an in-depth book explaining why the figures end up looking like they do in the hands of ignorant, manipulative or incompetent agenda-eers and professional victims.

The general population COULD understand the falsity of such pseudo-statistics with a bit of competent education and brain work, but people simply don't develop their thinking abilities very much in the disaster that's become the so-called "educational" system. The U.S. has been very hard hit by that, and the fact that the U.S. has had junk food the longest may have created some (hopefully reversible) problems in the DNA pool (some people who hate the West say such things, not about junk food, but about the DNA pool in the U.S.).

The average person could learn to assess so-called "science" better simply by being brought up with solid old-school education where brain work was expected and cultivated year after year as it used to be year after year through elementary and high school. Now, however, young adults have to guess at how many inches 2 1/2 feet translates to, or have to work in teams in unsuccessful attempts to figure out what 10% of $ 14.00 is, or look at you as if you're a lunatic if you expect them to be able to mentally figure out how much change to give if you give them $ 5.25 in payment for a $ 2.10 purchase. People really don't need to be so stupid -- most everyone can be EASILY educated far beyond that. It's "educators" who are at fault, and what they've done to school curricula.

People SHOULD have the brain power to understand that the margins of error in climate predictions, for example, are wider than the predicted changes, which means the predictions can't be taken seriously. I am not saying that climate change isn't important and doesn't need study, or that immediate serious action shouldn't be taken to reduce pollution -- but what has to be added to the social grasp of it all is how dangerous it is to make radical changes based on the biggest claims by those riding high flogging the climate horse.

Similarly, it wouldn't take much in the way of proper education to give the percentage of students who can learn enough basic critical thinking abilities and simple arithmetic skills to deal with food labels, prescription medicine warnings, fine print in contracts, instructions on bus transfers, and the like, but in the U.S. so much of that is now completely out of the grasp of a lot of people. Read the research of Linda S Gottfredson, for example, if you want to horrify yourself on the subject.

So, much as the video is correct in saying scientists can become corrupt, or be intimidated, or have all their personal interests invested in some pet theory they want to make a name and money off of, the deeper problem is the population that has come out of the disaster in the educational system. Even if science purified itself wondrously, would modern people and -- worse yet, the up-and-coming tidal wave of woke morons and their "professors" -- be able to competently think about the situations, choices and controversies they'd have to think about even in such a purified situation? That would be a bad bet, I think.

People SHOULD have the brain power to understand that the margins of error in climate predictions, for example, are wider than the predicted changes, which means the predictions can't be taken seriously.  I am not saying that climate change isn't important and doesn't need study, or that immediate serious action shouldn't be taken to reduce pollution -- but what has to be added to the social grasp of it all is how dangerous it is to make radical changes based on the biggest claims by those riding high flogging the climate horse.  

Similarly, it wouldn't take much in the way of proper education to give the percentage of students who can learn enough basic critical thinking abilities and simple arithmetic skills to deal with food labels, prescription medicine warnings, fine print in contracts, instructions on bus transfers, and the like, but in the U.S. so much of that is now completely out of the grasp of a lot of people.  Read the research of Linda S Gottfredson, for example, if you want to horrify yourself on the subject.

So, much as the video is correct in saying scientists can become corrupt, or be intimidated, or have all their personal interests invested in some pet theory they want to make a name and money off of, the deeper problem is the population that has come out of the disaster in the educational system.  Even if science purified itself wondrously, would modern people and -- worse yet, the up-and-coming tidal wave of woke morons and their "professors" --  be able to competently think about the situations, choices and controversies they'd have to think about even in such a purified situation? That would be a bad bet, I think.

Doubt, patience and precision are the markers of all true sciences.

textDisplay:
This is a ridiculous and lazy description of the problems of the way science research has trouble coming to better truth.
It is easy and fashionable to blame corporate influence or what is monetizable, but that is not the real issue; and even if it was a big issue, there is still a lot of public money for science (although there should be more)
The real issue for many scientists, even bigger than where their next grant will come from, is how can they keep up their reputation.
It is exactly the same for academics in the humanities which aren't competing for huge grants for the cost of doing research.
The problem is that the incentive structure is not designed in a way that promotes reaching the truth.
People are rewarded for publishing in "top teir" journals, and the publishing incentives don't allign with truth.
The fact that funding more research can confuse things shows that the model of research is broken. If it was working, then there would be no issue with more data (with some exceptions for when more data points mess up your model).
If a red team is creating problems by doing everything within the rules, it shows you that there was something with your rules.
All studies need to be pre-registered and study design decisions need to be explained, and all studies need to be published even if they come up negative.
The replication crisis that happened in psychology is not limited to psychology, it just happened to be picked up there.

"Why don't we trust science any more?"

I'm reminded of a story from John Michael Greer's "Dark Age America". Paraphrased: "I woman I knew went to a doctor for a chronic pain, and the doctor prescribed her some pills that made her miserable with the side effects. After weeks of debilitating misery and a trip to the E.R, she looked up her symptoms online and discovered it was an allergy to a food she was eating, which she promptly cut out of her diet and it solved her problem.

When she confronted her doctor with why he didn't recommend this, he replied "We prefer to medicate for that."

Now take this travesty, and expand it to the entirety of the "scientific world". "Scientists" are fallible people. They are subject to ideology, greed, avarice, corruption and malice. And it just so happens our money obsessed world rewards them for lying to us, and destroying our lives to further political agendas.

textDisplay:
Here's a fun example. As a PhD molecular biologist, I want to point out that all vaccine passports are meaningless, because the mRNA vaccines do not automatically stimulate your immune system to make antibodies like traditional vaccines do...

...mRNA vaccines are intended to stimulate the cells of your body to produce viral proteins, which then must be exported into your bloodstream so your white blood cells can find them and respond to them by making antibodies. This is totally different from traditional vaccines which contain the actual viral proteins already. With those, you just need to get jabbed and the desired result has been achieved. But with the mRNA vaccines, no protection occurs whatsoever after the jab unless and until a series of additional reactions take place in your body:
The mRNA in the jab must enter your cells, attach to the ribosomes, produce the Spike protein, export back out of the cell and into your bloodstream, and all this must happen without your body's own protein-making machinery causing any changes in that Spike protein. All of that is experimental and is probably not happening in most people.
Therefore, it is not enough to get jabbed with an mRNA vaccine, but more must happen before the desired result is achieved.
The ONLY way to "certify" or confirm that an mRNA vaccine against coronavirus has actually worked inside a person is to take a blood sample a few days after they get jabbed and then confirm that Spike protein was indeed made by your cells and sent into your bloodstream in its proper form. This test is not being done on anyone. And after a few days it is too late to go back and check.
There is no such thing as a valid vaccine passport for any mRNA vaccine to his day. They are all meaningless.

textDisplay: Science is a wonderful thing, but it must be endlessly challenged. Scientists once thought there was an 'ether' which allowed light particles to move through space. This opinion was held by scientists for ages before it was finally disproven and sceptics of the theory were dismissed (these days, they'd be 'fact checked'). Similarly, when Darwin first proposed the Theory of Evolution, many scientists  laughed and told him he was talking nonsense. Einstein, flummoxed by quantum entanglement called it 'spooky action at a distance' and struggled with quantum mechanics. Aristotle argued for a geocentric model but Plato and some of the pre-Socratic philosophers argued for a heliocentric one. Aristotle was taken up by the Catholic Church and it was religion that then stalled advances. Despite the claims of the video, there are real, qualified scientists who are still arguing the climate debate (usually, to what extent human activities AND natural ones are coalescing) and the efficacy of so-called net-zero solutions being instigated at great cost by advanced countries when poorer countries are desperately trying to drag themselves out of poverty using fossil fuels (China, India, most African countries). They ask if there are alternative solutions that would be more effective both in terms of economic burden and for the environment given we cannot ask billions of people to keep dying of poverty or simply wipe out 4-6 billion people to reduce our effect. Science does (and has) made mistakes; some of them spectacular. This is why it tests itself -- or used to. The problem is when corporate profit or political gain becomes a factor. Science should be globally funded and contributors should not be told what they are funding out of a long list of research options. Who decides what makes it onto the list? I would suggest other scientists without vested interests. Yes, we need to make sure money isn't wasted, but we need experts to determine what is 'waste'. As a non-scientist (unqualified, not uninterested) I cannot see how finding out how a shark behaves when drunk would help the shark or anyone else, but there may be legitimate reasons for wanting to find out (perhaps they have something in their brains that could resist the effects and offer a way to deal with alcoholism?) Science is no more infallible than any other human activity, but once something has been tested to destruction and come out on top, we run with it until something comes up that shows it's wrong. We still use Newton even though Einstein's theories have largely superseded him, since Newton's approach works perfectly well provided you're not dealing with high velocity and strong gravitational fields, but we use Einstein for GPS. Science is not the new god -- infallible and to be obeyed regardless. The strength of science is that is keeps questioning itself. Why don't we bow down to it on every single thing? Because we know they can make mistakes.

textDisplay: I am a bit annoyed with how this piece framed the issue as a sort of anti-capitalist message rather than one about the lack of government funding for basic science. Governments around the world don't contribute nearly enough to basic science which means that commercial science is overrepresented. There is nothing wrong with a company trying to find alternative reasons why something could be dangerous rather than immediately firing all their employees and wasting all their invested capital. The problem is that governments and private donors don't contribute nearly enough to basic science. By framing this as a battle between science and corporations, you have needlessly politized a non-political issue and alienated a huge percentage of the population and most of the people you are trying to convince. This documentary was designed to feed into the confirmation bias of the audience, not to promote genuine solutions or advance the dialogue in any way. Very disappointed.

textDisplay: Good documentary, until the last segment where it is asserted that man-made global warming is "indisputable".  That is politics or an agenda or an ideology speaking, not science.  The video shows ice falling off the edge of a glacier, which the viewer is to assume is "proof" that we are causing global warming and melting the glaciers.  The truth is that there is no evidence that Earth's climate is driven by carbon dioxide, and there is abundant evidence that climate change is driven by solar variation and other "space weather" causes external to anything that happens on Earth.  CO2-driven global warming is 'proved' by computer models that are incapable of accurately explaining or predicting actual climate changes on Earth.  Computer models will produce any results you choose.  All you have to do is adjust the values of the input variables in your climate model, and you can generate any outcome you like.  Nobody is denying that Earth's climate changes: that is obvious.  But the idea that humans are causing global warming (not climate change) by burning fossil fuels has become a religious belief unsupported by any actual evidence, and indeed contradicted by the evidence.
textOriginal: Good documentary, until the last segment where it is asserted that man-made global warming is "indisputable".  That is politics or an agenda or an ideology speaking, not science.  The video shows ice falling off the edge of a glacier, which the viewer is to assume is "proof" that we are causing global warming and melting the glaciers.  The truth is that there is no evidence that Earth's climate is driven by carbon dioxide, and there is abundant evidence that climate change is driven by solar variation and other "space weather" causes external to anything that happens on Earth.  CO2-driven global warming is 'proved' by computer models that are incapable of accurately explaining or predicting actual climate changes on Earth.  Computer models will produce any results you choose.  All you have to do is adjust the values of the input variables in your climate model, and you can generate any outcome you like.  Nobody is denying that Earth's climate changes: that is obvious.  But the idea that humans are causing global warming (not climate change) by burning fossil fuels has become a religious belief unsupported by any actual evidence, and indeed contradicted by the evidence.
